The paper deals with developing a formalism for expressing and reasoning with user preferences over collections of objects that satisfy functional requirements. This is a problem that is relevant to several areas of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), machine learning (cs.LG), social and information networks (cs.SI), and software engineering (cs.SE). The paper's focus on identifying optimal collections of objects based on user preferences suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.AI sub-category, followed by cs.DS and cs.LG. However, the paper's emphasis on the non-functional properties of collections and their relevance to complex system design and team formation also make cs.SE and cs.SI plausible sub-categories.
